diagnoses.name: Vulvodynia
diagnoses.description: Chronic pain or discomfort around the opening of your vagina, for which there's no identifiable cause and which lasts at least three months.

diagnoses.name: Iron Deficiency Anemia
diagnoses.description: A condition in which blood lacks adequate healthy red blood cells due to insufficient iron.

diagnoses.name: Urinary Tract Infection (UTI)
diagnoses.description: An infection in any part of the urinary system, kidneys, bladder, or urethra.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Fatigue Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A complex disorder characterized by extreme fatigue that can't be explained by any underlying medical condition.
common_treatments: Medication for pain and sleep problems

diagnoses.name: Fibromyalgia
diagnoses.description: A disorder characterized by widespread musculoskeletal pain accompanied by fatigue, sleep, memory, and mood issues.

diagnoses.name: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE)
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disease in which the body's immune system mistakenly attacks its own tissues, affecting the skin, joints, kidneys, brain, and other organs.

diagnoses.name: Pelvic Inflammatory Disease (PID)
diagnoses.description: An infection of the female reproductive organs. It usually occurs when sexually transmitted bacteria spread from your vagina to your uterus, fallopian tubes or ovaries.

diagnoses.name: HIV/AIDS
diagnoses.description: Human Immunodeficiency Virus (HIV) is a virus that attacks cells that help the body fight infection, making a person more vulnerable to other infections and diseases.

diagnoses.name: Diabetes Mellitus
diagnoses.description: A group of diseases that result in too much sugar in the blood (high blood glucose).

diagnoses.name: Attention-Deficit/Hyperactivity Disorder (ADHD)
diagnoses.description: A chronic condition including attention difficulty, hyperactivity, and impulsiveness.

diagnoses.name: Conversion disorder (Functional Neurological Symptom Disorder)
diagnoses.explanation: Pseudoseizures are often linked to psychological distress, making conversion disorder a possible diagnosis, manifesting physical symptoms without a medical cause.

diagnoses.name: Allergic Rhinitis
diagnoses.explanation: Can cause post-nasal drip and laryngitis due to inflammation and irritation of the nasal passages and throat.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Fatigue Syndrome
diagnoses.explanation: Characterized by non-restorative sleep among other symptoms like fatigue, muscle pain, and concentration issues.

diagnoses.name: Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease (GERD)
diagnoses.explanation: Can lead to post-nasal drip and laryngitis due to the irritation from stomach acids re-entering the esophagus and throat.

diagnoses.name: Angioedema
diagnoses.explanation: Angioedema itself as a diagnosis, given its inclusion already as a symptom, which could be idiopathic or related to an allergy or an immune disorder.

diagnoses.name: Hereditary Angioedema
diagnoses.explanation: A genetic form of angioedema that can cause repeated episodes of severe swelling.

diagnoses.name: Sleep Apnea
diagnoses.explanation: Can cause non-restorative sleep due to repeated interruptions in breathing, leading to poor sleep quality.

diagnoses.name: Anxiety Disorders
diagnoses.explanation: Can manifest physical symptoms such as pseudoseizures and non-restorative sleep, often tied to stress and psychological factors.

diagnoses.name: Upper Respiratory Infection
diagnoses.explanation: Can cause post-nasal drip, laryngitis, and general malaise, thus affecting sleep quality.

diagnoses.name: Vocal Cord Dysfunction
diagnoses.explanation: Can lead to symptoms like laryngitis and could be associated with stress-inducing pseudoseizures.

diagnoses.description: Asthma can lead to symptoms such as wheezing due to airway inflammation and narrowing.
This is a bleeding disorder that can cause easy bleeding due to a deficiency in or dysfunction of von Willebrand factor.
A genetic disorder that impairs the body's ability to make blood clots, leading to excessive bleeding.
Inflammation of the sinuses can lead to symptoms such as dysosmia (distorted sense of smell).
A chromosomal disorder in females that can result in delayed puberty and is sometimes associated with coagulopathies that could explain easy bleeding.
A condition associated with delayed or absent puberty and an impaired sense of smell.
Though primarily associated with irregular menstrual cycles and signs of hyperandrogenism, PCOS can indirectly affect puberty timing.
A group of lung conditions that block airflow and make breathing difficult, causing symptoms such as wheezing.
An allergic reaction that can cause sinus congestion and potentially affect the sense of smell (dysosmia).

Although directly mentioned in the symptoms, it's worth noting as a chronic condition where tissue similar to the lining inside the uterus grows outside of it, potentially causing a variety of symptoms including pelvic pain.

diagnoses: PANDAS (Pediatric Autoimmune Neuropsychiatric Disorders Associated with Streptococcal infections)

symptoms: dyspnea with normal pulmonary function tests

diagnoses.name: Major Depression
diagnoses.description: A mental disorder characterized by at least two weeks of low mood that is present across most situations.

diagnoses.name: Hypothyroidism
diagnoses.description: A condition in which the thyroid gland does not produce enough thyroid hormone, leading to a range of systemic effects.

diagnoses.name: Urinary Tract Infection
diagnoses.description: An infection in any part of the urinary system, kidneys, bladder, or urethra.

diagnoses.name: Neurocognitive Disorders
diagnoses.description: Disorders that are characterized by a decline from a previously attained level of cognitive functioning.

diagnoses.name: Vitamin B12 Deficiency
diagnoses.description: A condition resulting from not enough vitamin B12 which can lead to neurological difficulties.

diagnoses.name: Dementia
diagnoses.description: A chronic or persistent disorder of the mental processes caused by brain disease or injury and marked by memory disorders, personality changes, and impaired reasoning.

diagnoses.name: Anemia
diagnoses.description: A condition in which you lack enough healthy red blood cells to carry adequate oxygen to your body's tissues, having several types, including one related to vitamin B12 deficiency.

diagnoses.name: Dehydration
diagnoses.description: A condition that occurs when you use or lose more fluid than you take in, and your body doesn't have enough water and other fluids to carry out its normal functions.

diagnoses.name: Autoimmune encephalitis
diagnoses.description: A rare type of encephalitis that occurs when the body's immune system mistakenly attacks healthy brain cells, leading to inflammation of the brain.

diagnoses.name: Stroke
diagnoses.description: A condition where poor blood flow to the brain results in cell death. Symptoms may include difficulty speaking, walking, and understanding, as well as paralysis or numbness of the face, arm, or leg.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Idiopathic Angioedema
diagnoses.description: A condition characterized by recurrent episodes of severe swelling (angioedema) without a known cause.

diagnoses.name: Hereditary Angioedema
diagnoses.description: A genetic disorder causing repeated episodes of severe swelling. Unlike chronic idiopathic angioedema, it is caused by a genetic mutation.

diagnoses.name: Multiple Sclerosis
diagnoses.description: A disease in which the immune system eats away at the protective covering of nerves. Symptoms can include sensory neuropathies and attention deficit.

diagnoses.name: Hypothyroidism
diagnoses.description: A condition in which the thyroid gland doesn't produce enough thyroid hormone. Symptoms can include attention deficit and sometimes dyshydrotic eczema due to skin changes.

diagnoses.name: Diabetes Mellitus
diagnoses.description: A group of diseases that result in too much sugar in the blood (high blood glucose). Diabetes can lead to sensory neuropathies.

diagnoses.name: Oral Lichen Planus
diagnoses.description: An ongoing (chronic) inflammatory condition that affects mucous membranes inside your mouth. Oral lichen planus may appear as white, lacy patches; red, swollen tissues; or open sores, potentially mimicking leukoplakia.

diagnoses.name: Peripheral Neuropathy
diagnoses.description: A result of damage to your peripheral nerves, often causes weakness, numbness, and pain, usually in your hands and feet. It can also affect other areas and body functions including digestion and urination.

diagnoses.name: ADHD (Attention Deficit Hyperactivity Disorder)
diagnoses.description: A neurodevelopmental disorder characterized by a pattern of inattention and/or hyperactivity-impulsivity that interferes with functioning or development.

diagnoses.name: Contact Dermatitis
diagnoses.description: A skin rash caused by contact with a certain substance. It can lead to conditions such as dyshydrotic eczema.

diagnoses.name: Psoriasis
diagnoses.description: A chronic skin condition that speeds up the life cycle of skin cells. It causes cells to build up rapidly on the surface of the skin. The extra skin cells form scales and red patches that are itchy and sometimes painful. It can also feature dyshydrotic eczema-like presentations.

diagnoses.name: Behcet's Disease
diagnoses.description: An inflammatory disorder affecting multiple parts of the body, including the blood vessels which could explain the occurrence of aneurysms.

diagnoses.name: Vasculitis
diagnoses.description: A group of disorders that destroy blood vessels by inflammation which might relate to aneurysms.

diagnoses.name: Marfan Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A genetic disorder that affects the body's connective tissue, leading to aneurysms.

diagnoses.name: Ehlers-Danlos Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A group of disorders that affect connective tissues supporting the skin, bones, blood vessels, and many other organs and tissues. Might be related to aneurysms.

diagnoses.name: Lichen Planus
diagnoses.description: A condition that forms an itchy rash on the skin or in the mouth which could explain the leukoplakia.

diagnoses.name: Tuberculosis
diagnoses.description: A bacterial infection that can spread through the lymph nodes and bloodstream to any organ in your body but is usually found in the lungs. This might relate to otitis media in its extrapulmonary manifestations.

diagnoses.name: Wegener's Granulomatosis
diagnoses.description: A rare disorder that causes inflammation of the blood vessels in your nose, sinuses, throat, lungs, and kidneys. It could explain aneurysms and otitis media.

diagnoses.name: Fibromuscular Dysplasia
diagnoses.description: A condition that causes abnormal growth or development of cells in the walls of blood vessels that can lead to aneurysms.

diagnoses.name: Attention Deficit Hyperactivity Disorder (ADHD)
diagnoses.description: A brain disorder marked by an ongoing pattern of inattention and/or hyperactivity-impulsivity that interferes with functioning or development.

diagnoses.name: Tinnitus - Not a diagnosis itself but a symptom of underlying conditions
diagnoses.description: Often associated with hearing loss, ear injuries, or circulatory system disorders. Given in connection with otitis media and possibly influenced by the vascular issues related to aneurysms.

diagnoses: Hashimoto's thyroiditis leading to transient hyperthyroidism

symptoms: dyspnea with normal pulmonary function tests

diagnoses.name: Migraine with Aura
diagnoses.description: A type of headache that is accompanied by visual disturbances or other types of aura. In some cases, migraine with aura can present with symptoms such as aphasia, phonophobia (sensitivity to sound), and numbness or weakness.

diagnoses.name: Stroke
diagnoses.description: A medical condition where the blood supply to part of the brain is interrupted or reduced, causing brain cells to die. Symptoms can include aphasia, weakness, numbness, and in some cases, vertigo.

diagnoses.name: Transient Ischemic Attack (TIA)
diagnoses.description: Often called a mini-stroke, a TIA is a temporary period of symptoms similar to those of a stroke. It can include aphasia, vertigo, weakness, and numbness.

diagnoses.name: Multiple Sclerosis (MS)
diagnoses.description: A disease in which the immune system eats away at the protective covering of nerves. MS can cause symptoms such as weakness, numbness, and in some cases, aphasia or vertigo.

diagnoses.name: Brain Tumor
diagnoses.description: A mass or growth of abnormal cells in the brain. Depending on its location, a brain tumor can cause aphasia, numbness, weakness, and sometimes vertigo.

diagnoses.name: Ménière’s Disease
diagnoses.description: A disorder of the inner ear that can lead to dizzy spells (vertigo) and hearing loss. In some cases, patients might experience symptoms that resemble aphasia due to auditory processing issues.

diagnoses.name: Vertebrobasilar Insufficiency
diagnoses.description: Occurs when there is reduced blood flow to the back part of the brain. Symptoms can include vertigo, phonophobia, weakness, numbness, and occasionally aphasia.

diagnoses.name: Epilepsy
diagnoses.description: A neurological disorder marked by sudden recurrent episodes of sensory disturbance, loss of consciousness, or convulsions, associated with abnormal electrical activity in the brain. Some forms of epilepsy may lead to aphasia or sensations like vertigo.

diagnoses.name: Acoustic Neuroma
diagnoses.description: A benign tumor on the main nerve leading from the inner ear to the brain. Symptoms might include vertigo, numbness, and if the tumor affects certain brain areas, aphasia.

diagnoses.name: Vestibular Neuronitis
diagnoses.description: An inflammation of the vestibular nerve, which can cause vertigo. Patients may also experience symptoms like numbness or weakness if the inflammation affects adjacent nerves.
A type of headache accompanied by visual disturbances (scotoma, scintillation), sensitivity to sound (phonophobia), and can include temporary motor weakness.
A common type of migraine characterized by recurrent headaches that are moderate to severe, typically pulsating, and often accompanied by nausea, phonophobia, and photophobia.
The most common type of primary headache. Its symptoms include a dull, constant headache with no other neurologic deficits.
Known for severe unilateral temple or orbital pain, cluster headaches occur in groups or 'clusters' and may accompany photophobia or phonophobia, though less commonly than in migraines.
A medical condition where poor blood flow to the brain results in cell death. Symptoms can include headaches, weakness, and problems with vision such as scotoma.

Often called a mini-stroke, a TIA produces similar symptoms to a stroke, including headache, weakness, and occasional visual symptoms, but usually lasts only a few minutes and causes no permanent damage.
A chronic autoimmune disease affecting the central nervous system, causing varied neurological symptoms that can include visual disturbances (scotoma, scintillation) and weakness.
Abnormal cell growth in the brain that can cause headaches, weakness, and vision problems among other symptoms.

A disorder of the inner ear causing severe dizziness (vertigo), ringing in the ears (tinnitus), hearing loss, and a feeling of fullness or congestion in the ear. Headache and phonophobia can also be present.
Increased pressure inside the skull without a detectable cause, leading to headaches, visual disturbances, and possibly weakness if nerves are affected.

diagnoses.name: Migraine
diagnoses.description: A neurological condition that can cause multiple symptoms including, but not limited to, severe, recurring headaches and sensory disturbances.

diagnoses.name: Multiple Sclerosis
diagnoses.description: A chronic illness involving your central nervous system. The immune system attacks myelin, leading to demyelination, which causes a range of symptoms including weakness, numbness, and difficulty walking.

diagnoses.name: Vestibular Neuritis
diagnoses.description: Inflammation of the vestibular nerve, a nerve in the ear that helps control balance. Symptoms can include vertigo, dizziness, imbalance, nausea, and sometimes hearing loss.

diagnoses.name: Meniere's Disease
diagnoses.description: A disorder of the inner ear that can lead to dizzy spells (vertigo) and hearing loss. In most cases, Meniere's disease affects only one ear.

diagnoses.name: Brain Tumor
diagnoses.description: A mass or growth of abnormal cells in your brain or close to your brain. Symptoms can include headaches, changes in speech or hearing, balance and walking problems, and weakness in one part of the body.

diagnoses.name: Lyme Disease
diagnoses.description: An infectious disease caused by the Borrelia bacterium which is spread by ticks. Early symptoms may include headache, fatigue, fever, and a skin rash. If untreated, it can spread to the joints, heart, and the nervous system.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Inflammatory Demyelinating Polyneuropathy (CIDP)
diagnoses.description: A neurological disorder characterized by progressive weakness and impaired sensory function in the legs and arms. The disorder, which is related to the immune system attacking the nervous system, can present with symptoms similar to those listed.

diagnoses.name: Acoustic Neuroma
diagnoses.description: A noncancerous and usually slow-growing tumor that develops on the main nerve leading from your inner ear to your brain. Symptoms may include hearing loss, ringing in your ear, dizziness, and loss of balance.

diagnoses.name: Vitamin B12 Deficiency
diagnoses.description: Lack of B12 can cause various neurological problems, including tingling in the hands and feet, weakness, loss of balance, and cognitive disturbances.

diagnoses.name: Anxiety Disorders
diagnoses.description: Excessive worry or fear which can cause a variety of somatic symptoms including headache, nausea, weakness, and dizziness. Although less likely to cause all the symptoms collectively, anxiety can significantly contribute to their severity.
